  "prompt": "What is a pulmonary embolism?",
  "response": "A pulmonary embolism (PE) is a medical condition where one or more arteries in the lungs become blocked by a blood clot. These clots can originate from other parts of the body, most commonly the legs, a condition known as deep vein thrombosis (DVT). When the clot travels to the lung, it can obstruct the blood flow and lead to serious complications.\n\nSymptoms of a pulmonary embolism can vary but typically include:\n- Sudden shortness of breath\n- Chest pain, which may be sharp and worsen with deep breathing or coughing\n- Cough, sometimes with blood-streaked sputum\n- Rapid heart rate\n- Lightheadedness or fainting\n\nRisk factors for pulmonary embolism include:\n- Prolonged immobility (such as during long flights or bed rest)\n- Surgery, especially orthopedic surgery\n- Certain medical conditions like cancer or heart disease\n- Smoking\n- Use of oral contraceptives or hormone replacement therapy\n- History of DVT or PE\n- Obesity\n\nDiagnosis of PE is often done through imaging tests such as CT pulmonary angiography, ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) scan, or ultrasound of the legs to detect DVT. Blood tests like D-dimer can also help indicate the presence of abnormal clotting activity in the body.\n\nImmediate treatment for pulmonary embolism usually involves anticoagulant medications to prevent further clotting and, in severe cases, thrombolytics to dissolve the clot. In some situations, surgical intervention such as the placement of a vena cava filter or embolectomy might be necessary.\n\nPulmonary embolism is a potentially life-threatening condition that requires swift medical attention. Recognizing symptoms early and seeking prompt treatment can significantly improve outcomes.",
